00:01.400 --> 00:10.860
Dr. Williamson first of all we'd like to begin with what you're working on right
now. I'm working on a novel called The Queen of the Legion. There's another

00:10.860 --> 00:16.160
story about the Legion of Space, a series that I started back in the early 30s.

00:18.660 --> 00:27.420
Is it going to be serialized like the others? Well here's hoping the market's
sort of uncertain. Fred Pohl gave me a contract for it a couple of years ago and

00:27.420 --> 00:36.700
I was president of the Science Fiction Writers of America and involved in other
things, and it has taken time to do, but it's finally falling together, and I'm

00:36.700 --> 00:48.280
putting it into my new word processor, and I'm pretty enthusiastic about it now.
The main character is a girl, and at first I was sort of uncertain whether I

00:48.280 --> 00:56.780
could be convincing and presenting a woman's point of view, but I've sort of
fallen in love with Jill by now. I think I know her pretty well and like her,

00:56.780 --> 01:07.180
and I hope the readers do. Have you finished that trilogy with Frederik Pohl,
the one on the Dyson sphere, the three volumes on that? No, I'm sorry to say we

01:07.180 --> 01:21.900
haven't. I finished my part of the second volume some years ago, I think. A year
and a half ago, Judy-Lynn Del Rey gave us a revised contract with a larger

01:21.900 --> 01:36.680
advance. and her idea then was to publish all three proposed volumes in one
thick volume. Fred was going to get it out last March at that time, but that's

01:36.680 --> 01:48.700
the last I've heard about it. He's promoting his work, he's involved in many
projects, and that's always been the history of working with him. He's a great

01:48.700 --> 01:58.980
collaborator, but he takes his time, So I have hope that he'll eventually get
back to it. Have you—recently you've been redoing some of the Humanoid material,

01:59.020 --> 02:07.620
too, correct? Have you finished—is there a novel that's come out of that?
There's a new novel called The Humanoid Touch that I finished well over a year

02:07.620 --> 02:19.180
ago, and it will be published, I think, this summer, in a limited signed edition
from Fantasia Press with a whole Red Hart cover this November. Part of that was

02:19.180 --> 02:29.440
serialized and analog, wasn't it? And it all reprinted or printed in the middle
of it under the title Humanoid Universe. There was a reference in that story or

02:29.440 --> 02:38.580
somewhere to a book called Ten Trillion Wise Machines. What's that? Well, that
was my second title. First I was going to call a novel a humanoid universe, and

02:38.580 --> 02:52.120
Fred didn't like that. And I wanted to call it Ten Trillion Wise Machines, which
is a title I like. but people wanted the name Humanoids in the title. And also,

02:52.320 --> 03:02.440
that's pretty long to go on a book jacket. And J.K. Klein, a science fiction
photographer, is the man who came up with the title Humanoid Tarch, which I

03:02.440 --> 03:11.980
think is appropriate and brief, and has humanoids in it, and I'm very happy with
it. Perhaps you could explain the difference between humanoids and androids and

03:11.980 --> 03:20.000
robots. Well, in my mind the robots

03:20.000 --> 03:32.300
are a mechanical man and the humanoids are a type of robot that is made out of
plastic and steel and operated by remote control by computers and so forth. And

03:32.300 --> 03:44.020
androids, as I used the term in the comitre many years ago, and I think it's
generally used, is a, let's say, a meat machine, a synthetic or artificial human

03:44.020 --> 03:55.520
being made out of flesh and blood. The sort of thing that is possible to produce
these days or in the near future by genetic engineering, I'd say. That is,

03:55.640 --> 03:58.740
androids bleed and human rights drip grease.

04:02.440 --> 04:08.680
it's interesting that you're going back and doing some of the material that you
started, well not started with, but that you've done before the Legion material,

04:08.880 --> 04:19.900
the humanoids and so forth was it 1928 you published, you began publishing in
the first story I was published in the November December 1928 that share of

04:19.900 --> 04:29.980
amazing and I've been a science fiction writer ever since that was that was in
the tradition of merit wasn't it more of a fantasy kind of pretty much at that

04:29.980 --> 04:44.120
time I was infatuated with Merritt I haven't re-read him for many years lest the
spell be gone but the first stories I wrote well were for at least a time sit a

04:44.120 --> 04:57.080
purple color illustrated with two many adjectives later I began to try for more
convincing settings and stronger characters and fewer adjectives. What made you

04:57.080 --> 05:10.700
start writing the ... Well, I grew up on a sand hill farm in the south part of
this county when times were pretty grim and I, well, I wanted to be some sort of

05:10.700 --> 05:23.480
scientist without any direction or means to get a scientific education and And a
few months after Gernsback started the old Amazing, I came across some copies of

05:23.480 --> 05:38.180
it. And I was immediately fascinated with experiments that worked with travel in
time and spaceships to other worlds and all sorts of wonderful things. It's been

05:38.180 --> 05:50.500
an important share of my life ever since. Did you start for the money? Was it
money in love? Well, the money was well almost immaterial. I got $25 for that

05:50.500 --> 06:03.480
first story eventually. And after a couple of years I earned enough writing
science fiction so I didn't have to do anything else. But half the secret was

06:03.480 --> 06:16.560
that I wasn't married and was willing to live economically. So I certainly
didn't do it for the money. After two years in college I was offered a student

06:16.560 --> 06:28.900
assistantship in the chemistry lab. I could have had different careers, chemist
probably, I was more fascinated with science fiction than I was with science by

06:28.900 --> 06:38.860
that time, though I have tried to keep up as best a language can with what's
going on in science. Was the account true that I read in one place where you

06:38.860 --> 06:47.220
didn't know that your story had been accepted until you saw the magazine on the
lengths? That's true. I wrote these stories on an old Remington Biscuit model

06:47.220 --> 06:56.800
typewriter and a purple ribbon and two or three of them came back one of them
was with a mispelled word in the title and the metal man never did come back and

06:56.800 --> 07:14.380
I was over at Canyon Texas walking by a newsstand one day and I saw my metal man
on the cover of Amazing it was quite a thrill what was it What was it like to

07:14.380 --> 07:22.240
you to write for the pulp, say, through the 30s and so forth? Did you feel a
part of something, or did you feel isolated out here? I mean there weren't many

07:22.240 --> 07:33.660
around here who could share your interest. Was there? The science fiction world
has always been a sort of special community, where I suppose we felt we had our

07:33.660 --> 07:44.520
own special handle on science in the future and in the shape of things to come.
and though I didn't see other science fiction people very often, I read the

07:44.520 --> 07:58.760
stories and read letters in the magazines and so forth. In those days, before
the paperbacks and before TV and before the comics, my people read a lot more

07:58.760 --> 08:08.370
for entertainment than they do nowadays and there were really three sorts of
magazines. There were the quality magazines like Harper's And those scribblers

08:08.370 --> 08:20.430
and light it for people with brains and slicks printed on coated paper that
would take good advertising for people with money to spend. The poets for people

08:20.430 --> 08:36.110
who had neither brains nor money. but we had a lot of fun in the parts even. We
were looked down upon widely. And eventually, science fiction got recognized as

08:36.110 --> 08:45.250
being not entirely without brains, let's say. And nowadays, there's a little bit
of money in it sometimes. Back then, it wasn't called science fiction, was it?

08:45.650 --> 08:55.410
No. When I started, my first story was printed as scientifiction. and Hugo
Gernsback ran the word science and fiction together. He invented the term

08:55.410 --> 09:06.790
science fiction in 29, I think. At that time, you had to explain what it was. I
used to say it was adventure stories with a science background. Well, wasn't

09:06.790 --> 09:21.550
Gernsback, didn't he want more scientifically-oriented stories? He preached the
gospel that science fiction was sugar-coated science, that was education and he

09:21.550 --> 09:34.730
got a whole panel of experts with degrees that were supposed to vet the science
and science wonder-stories when he started that. But actually, I think that was

09:34.730 --> 09:49.890
a much for him to impress the readers as anything else because he did use true
science in his stories when he could get it, but he also printed a lot of

09:49.890 --> 10:00.330
stories that were pretty wild. I think always in the magazine, the adventure
element was more important than the science. I've only seen a few copies of

10:00.330 --> 10:11.770
those very early pulps. They say the amazing stories. That's a pretty big size.
Well, the size that time is nowadays. Were there other sizes too or types? and

10:11.770 --> 10:26.870
Amazing was that size, and Wonder Stories when Gernsback started that. But they
were also, and they were hardly regular popes, because in the beginning, Amazing

10:26.870 --> 10:35.910
was filled up with reprints of classic science fiction, and the rights were so
low that professional writers didn't write for them. so they wrote news stories

10:35.910 --> 10:49.970
that are mostly written by amateurs such as myself. But the pulp magazines were
published in chains with... well, sometimes quite different magazines that were

10:49.970 --> 11:05.970
mass economists because of the covers all in the same press run and so forth.
and they had a standard smaller size. Astounding came along from Clayton, first

11:05.970 --> 11:17.970
his Astounding Stories of Super Science. It was the pulp size. What was the
rate, or average rate, for stories in those days? Well, Gernsback paid a half a

11:17.970 --> 11:31.370
cent a word or less, which meant whether you'd get $25 for a short story and $75
for a novelette. But Clayton paid $0.02 a word and up, which is one reason maybe

11:31.370 --> 11:47.190
the Clayton magazines went bankrupt in the Great Depression. But that meant that
I could pound up 4,000 words a day for two days and earn $160, which was a

11:47.190 --> 11:57.210
fabulous feat for a farm kid in depression days. That was a pretty good income
back then. It was. It was a lot of money. Did you get much reader response? Did

11:57.210 --> 12:08.550
fans or readers ever? Well, of course I didn't know many people in the locality
who read science fiction, but in those days the backs of the magazines were

12:08.550 --> 12:18.810
filled up with letters and tiny types from readers. That was the principal
reader response. I think the editors favored them because they didn't have to

12:18.810 --> 12:31.210
pay for the letters and they were interesting to us I used to write them myself
as well as reading. It was the beginning of fandom, I suppose.

12:35.430 --> 12:45.750
From what I can gather, reading back on your publishing history and so forth,
through the 30s, late 20s, early 30s, you were mostly writing, I guess I would

12:45.750 --> 12:54.930
call it space opera, the Legion material. I've never objected to space opera. I
still think it's wonderful. and I even think that Star Wars could have been made

12:54.930 --> 13:06.970
out of my legend stories as well as it was from something else. I enjoyed Star
Wars tremendously as a sort of adolescent daydream and well, the pulp readers

13:06.970 --> 13:24.350
were mostly young and as naive as I was and the space opera was a sort of
symbolic escape from all sorts of things. I notice I'm not sure how I would

13:24.350 --> 13:33.950
phrase this a change or a deepening or a more serious aspect to your fiction
that begins in the late 30s would I be right in saying that do you? probably I

13:33.950 --> 13:44.150
was growing up and the readers were growing up that's something that's been
going on in science fiction at least in American science fiction all along I

13:44.150 --> 13:54.430
think you can draw a distinction between let's say European or mainstream
science fiction, on the one hand, which has always been recognized and treated

13:54.430 --> 14:07.990
as literature, a part of American science fiction which was looked down on. But
as the readers of that grew older, some of them started writing, some of them

14:07.990 --> 14:21.530
started editing magazines, most of them outgrew science But some of them didn't.
So there was a continual increase in education, the sophistication, and so forth

14:21.530 --> 14:33.750
in the whole field. Maybe you should call it a Diversification because there's
still a readership for Edgar Rice Burroughs and Robert E Howard and whatever. There

14:33.750 --> 14:47.570
are also people who are former fans who are now academic fans who are teaching
science fiction courses and writing scholarly articles on science fiction to

14:47.570 --> 15:02.310
publish the Paris test and so forth. So essentially the field is just
diversified into all sorts of levels and areas of interest. Did Campbell

15:02.310 --> 15:12.350
influence the way you wrote fiction at all? Don W. Campbell? Yes, I think he
influenced the way nearly everybody wrote science fiction. Because when he

15:12.350 --> 15:29.610
became editor of Amazing, and later changed the name to Analog, he had the best,
highest-payer market in the field. He was, well, let's say science fiction was

15:29.610 --> 15:42.110
serious to him as a way of speculating about science and its impact in the
future of mankind, and so forth. He was tremendously inventive, he was full of

15:42.110 --> 15:55.330
ideas that he shared very freely. And everybody who was writing science fiction
for those years was influenced by Campbell, it seems to me, whether directly or

15:55.330 --> 16:07.790
not. if they weren't trying to write for him and reading his letters, they were
reading such writers as Heinlein and De Camp and Sturgeon and a dozen others

16:07.790 --> 16:22.450
who were Campbell writers. Some people resented Campbell and felt that it was an
effort to write for him. Campbell Hanan used to complain that you couldn't sell him

16:22.450 --> 16:38.250
adult sex. Campbell and I thought so much alike so that I always felt at home with
his magazine and enjoyed working with him. And he gave me occasional very useful

16:38.250 --> 16:49.870
suggestions that I used, and he never did, well, I did my material heavily or
tried to persuade me to say anything I didn't want to say. I believe that

16:49.870 --> 17:01.290
personally he was optimistic about science in the future. But when I wrote such
a pessimistic dystopian thing as The Folded Hangs, well, he published as it was

17:01.290 --> 17:11.570
and ask for more. I was going to ask you about that with folded hands. You sold
that one to Campbell? That was sold to him? He suggested a sequel to it. He was

17:11.570 --> 17:22.990
more fanatic for various things that look sort of crackpot nowadays including
Joseph Ryan in parapsychology. And he suggested if people's hands were folded,

17:23.050 --> 17:34.930
they would use their minds, they would develop psychological powers and perhaps
defeat the humanoids. I felt that the humanoids couldn't be defeated, so that

17:34.930 --> 17:46.250
the ending of my novel was sort of ambiguous. But he published it as I sent it
to him, and the reader seemed to like it well enough. I was interested in what

17:46.250 --> 17:54.190
you wrote in the afterward to one of the recent editions of The Humanoids, the
way your interpretation of it's changed. Like, didn't you used to see yourself,

17:54.190 --> 18:04.690
you said, a romantic and the humanoids were bad, but then you'd altered that?
Well, I think so. That is at one level since the humanoids are machines, the

18:04.690 --> 18:17.630
perfect machine, as I recently stated, the theme, the perfect machine would be
perfectly dreadful because it would take away all human freedom and

18:17.630 --> 18:32.710
responsibility and opportunity for achievement. But as I came to look at the
story more, it seemed to me the essential human conflict in it is the conflict

18:32.710 --> 18:47.630
between the individual and society, and the people in the stories are in a,
let's say, a complex and painful emotional situation because the humanoids are

18:47.630 --> 19:00.090
meant to be good. They're presented as benign. They're trying to assure the
safety and happiness of mankind. And in doing this, they destroy freedom. And I

19:00.090 --> 19:10.570
decided eventually that this reflects my own very early childhood experience
when people were overprotecting me because they loved me for my own good, but

19:10.570 --> 19:21.010
still I couldn't help with deep resentment because they wouldn't let me do so
many things I wanted to do. And I feel, by the way, that the conflict between

19:21.010 --> 19:35.790
the individual society is a basic material of most literature, really, and I
approach it in all sorts of ways. at one level why literature socializes. It

19:35.790 --> 19:53.270
teaches us unselfishness and patriotism and obedience and all sorts of social
virtues. And at another level why it can be critical of the influence of society

19:53.270 --> 20:06.190
on the individual. In Ibsen especially he presents character after character who
is destroyed by the pressures of society or by conceding too much to society. In

20:06.190 --> 20:17.190
that novel, The Humanoids, Ironsmith, it seemed to me, represented society or
conformity and so forth. When I first read the book, I kept thinking he was

20:17.190 --> 20:25.630
going to turn into an evil character, a villain, but you never made him a
villain. He remained, I don't know, a friendly person, a helpful person, but

20:25.630 --> 20:32.390
simply one who was siding with the humanoids. Has your attitude toward him
changed since you've written the book? I think maybe I understand him better.

20:32.710 --> 20:44.390
When I was writing the novel, I don't think I really understood him except that
he was a fascinating enigma. That is, he was a likable guy. He wasn't caught up

20:44.390 --> 20:56.670
in the conflict that my main character was. He got along with the humanoids, and
they befriended him. they befriended him, and it occurred to me later that he's

20:56.670 --> 21:09.230
the example of the person who does conform to society, who accepts its
limitations, and as a result of that, is unable to live a more relaxed and

21:09.230 --> 21:23.590
richer life, in contrast to the person always in conflict with society, who, in
the worst instance, has to destroy himself because nobody can live alone. If you

21:23.590 --> 21:34.930
were to continue with the humanoid, further than you have, the humanoid stories,
would you ultimately have them, man, being happy under their care? Would they

21:34.930 --> 21:49.250
stop conquering the universe? Well, I haven't planned to do that. In fact, I was
reluctant to write any more about them until Fred Kohl offered me a contract I

21:49.250 --> 22:03.430
couldn't refuse. but in this new novel, The Humanoid Touch, where I tried to
work out an alternative that doesn't involve the destruction of the humanoids

22:03.430 --> 22:19.350
but does offer an alternate way of life that is an escape from. I don't know how
readers will react, but the story... I enjoyed writing and I have hopes for it.

22:19.350 --> 22:29.790
Well, when you finished with folded hands in that time period, you must have
gotten some response from readers or editors that it was kind of pessimistic or

22:29.790 --> 22:40.810
dystopian because you wrote The Equalizer, didn't you? It was sort of a counter?
Well, more or less. In fact, with folded hands, the humanoid stories were the

22:40.810 --> 22:52.470
first project that I undertook after I got home from World War II. I was an Air
Force's weather forecaster, in the Southwest Pacific when the bomb went off, and

22:52.470 --> 23:07.530
the atomic bomb cast a dark mushroom cloud over all science fiction, and much
science fiction was, well, suddenly pessimistic about the future, thus this was

23:07.530 --> 23:17.730
the setting in which I wrote For Human Knowledge, and when I started to write
it, I originally felt that they could be somehow conquered or disposed of or

23:17.730 --> 23:30.290
whatever, And then as I worked with them, I realized that logically and
artistically they were invincible. So I gave up in the middle of a ... or before

23:30.290 --> 23:46.650
I got in the middle of a novel, I planned and wrote The Equalizer as an example
of, say that technology is benevolent. that can be used to make a really better

23:46.650 --> 24:00.330
world. Then I came back to the humanoids and replotted it with folded hands. I
would just have one more question on the humanoid books, the humanoid material.

24:00.970 --> 24:11.210
I guess some of the readers, some responses I've read about it have been kind of
confused, or on both sides of the question as to what you meant. My concern

24:11.210 --> 24:22.170
would be, are you optimistic about man and his future and his relation to
machines? Can he control them? Can he survive them? Are they going to destroy

24:22.170 --> 24:35.470
him or in his nature? Well, I think I'm optimistic. I try to be optimistic. I
think that once we have technology, we can't unhave it. We can't put the genie

24:35.470 --> 24:47.950
back in the bottle. we have to accept it and live with it. I think that people
who want to return to the 18th century or to the garden of Eden or whatever are

24:47.950 --> 25:02.730
simply trying to whistle in the dark. And I think the technology can solve
problems if we use it to solve problems. So I'm more optimistic than stories. I

25:02.730 --> 25:15.290
think that to a considerable extent, And a story should have its own independent
theme, more or less independently of what the writer thinks or believes when I'm

25:15.290 --> 25:27.170
trying to write a story, why I like to stop after I have a reasonable start and
look at it and decide what the theme is, and then rearrange it if necessary to

25:27.170 --> 25:30.590
give it the strongest impact that I can.

25:33.510 --> 25:42.410
Do you have any questions in this area David? Not about the humanoids. I have
one backing up a little bit. It seems that many of your stories have anticipated

25:42.410 --> 25:52.890
scientific discoveries such as Dark Star Station anticipated neutron stars. How
did you get the ideas about that? Well it's hard to say except that I've always

25:52.890 --> 26:04.710
been fascinated with science, science is, well you can put it as a sort of
mystery story of what the world is, the universe is, about its origins, and

26:04.710 --> 26:19.930
development, and meaning, with effort going on in a hundred fields of science to
unravel the mystery. And I've always tried to read science magazines and science

26:19.930 --> 26:35.730
books, and keep up with what's happening. And I'm concerned with what the
universe is, and sometimes I have speculations of my own that will later confirm

26:35.730 --> 26:36.110
this.

26:40.410 --> 26:48.950
I notice a number of stories, and in some of your novels, especially in the late
30s, early 40s, where you describe totalitarian kind of societies, like

26:48.950 --> 26:59.190
breakdown. Was that story, I think, with the square deal, if I remember
correctly? and in that area where the humans are struggling to overcome sort of

26:59.190 --> 27:09.610
a totalitarian society. Was that in any way related to the world situation? I
think so. At that time, of course, we were faced with Hitler and a little bit

27:09.610 --> 27:25.470
later with Stalin. And I think there were too many stories at that time that
placed us in a struggle with a totalitarian situation. And, of course, that is

27:25.470 --> 27:38.630
sort of an ultimate statement of the problem of the society versus the
individual, the individual being destroyed, at least his freedom erased by a

27:38.630 --> 27:46.930
totally arbitrary society. If I'm remembering correctly, that story breakdown,

27:49.770 --> 27:58.610
wasn't that the one where Boss Kellen was in control and his son wanted to go to
the stars, right? The research. And the boss said stay on the Earth, forget

27:58.610 --> 28:10.370
that. I took that as very characteristic of your fiction. You have to have a
goal, a challenge. You have to keep wanting to go rather than be structured and

28:10.370 --> 28:21.110
restricted in a society. Kind of something to look forward to, to try for. I
think we all need With goals and promises and escapes and freedom and

28:21.110 --> 28:36.330
realization of possibility, it seems to me that when we're caught in this
paradoxical situation between the needs of the individual and the demands of the

28:36.330 --> 28:49.050
society. We can't live completely alone. We have to have a support and love and
so forth and other people. But if society demands too much, it's destructive. So

28:49.050 --> 29:01.830
there's no final answer to it. It's a matter of a precarious set of compromises
that goes on as long as we live. And some people make compromises more

29:01.830 --> 29:15.130
successfully than others. I did my dissertation on H.G. Wells who I think was a
very successful compromiser with society and lived a very rich and varied life

29:15.130 --> 29:30.530
and enjoyed the love of many gifted women and so on and so forth. In contrast
with a friend of his named Gissing, George Gissing, a man who matched society or

29:30.530 --> 29:39.890
tried to head on and died young and bitter and poor and defeated. Yeah, didn't
you sort of, if I remember one place, you sort of, you didn't say this, but I

29:39.890 --> 29:47.090
got the impression Gissing was the, say, the Forrester type and the Humanoids,
and Wells was more the Ironsmith type? But that fits my own notion. Yeah, yeah.

29:47.090 --> 29:59.890
I don't know if I ever said it. Do you take Wells to be pessimistic about man's
future progress? Well, I did my dissertation on Wells and title Chapter of

29:59.890 --> 30:13.130
Progress. It is a critic of progress and it seems to me that he is there saying
in several ways I would recognize that progress is not all we'd like it to be,

30:13.330 --> 30:28.450
that our universe is hostile or certainly not friendly to progress, and that we
have a barrier in the animal nature of mankind, which he explores in such things

30:28.450 --> 30:40.030
as the island of Dr. Moreau, and then a farther the notion that progress limits
itself. That is, as an evolutionary struggle, and I think Wells was a Darwinian

30:40.570 --> 30:57.370
if you stop struggling you sink back so you never can reach a ultimate peak and
stay there. But on the other hand, Wells must have had hope for something better

30:57.370 --> 31:11.390
because he spent most of his life in a struggle to build a better society, to
educate us and warn us and shape us for a world state and he died, I think, more

31:11.390 --> 31:20.170
or less in bitter and despair but still it seems to be that most of his life was
lived in hope.

31:24.250 --> 31:35.810
I want to ask you a little bit too. It's fascinating to me the way science
fiction caught on and began through the 30s and so forth. Oh, around 1939, if I

31:35.810 --> 31:44.270
remember, people like Asimov and Heinlein and I think it's pronounced Van Vogt,
is that correct? Van Vogt. Van Vogt, okay. They started publishing around that

31:44.270 --> 31:57.850
time. Were you reading these people as they started? They all started in Campbell's
magazine. Astounding, he was, well, I don't know whether you'd say So, Campbell

31:57.850 --> 32:14.670
discovered them, and they discovered him, but it was, let's say, a small group
with a great deal of fellowship or fellow understanding and so forth. It was an

32:14.670 --> 32:31.990
exciting period in which to be alive. In 1940, I spent about a year in Los
Angeles. I spent many Saturday evenings at Bob Heinlein's home on Laurel Canyon,

32:32.230 --> 32:43.930
Hollywood, when we had what we called the Mañana Literary Society. It was not an
organization. It was just a group of friends, but we got together and talked

32:43.930 --> 32:54.130
science fiction. and we were all reading each other's science fiction when it
was published. And the field was a lot closer knit than it is now because

32:54.130 --> 33:08.170
everybody could read all that anybody published. It was a little group and we
were much closer together and, by and large, we were friends. Have you kept up,

33:08.210 --> 33:21.150
you know, personal what? Well, I guess as president AFWA and so forth, or SWA,
SFWA Science in America. That's right, yeah. Well, I still have a lot of old

33:21.150 --> 33:34.110
friendships and make new friends, but we have upwards of 500 members in the
organization. And nearly all of them have published at least a few stories.

33:36.730 --> 33:50.890
And publishers, paperback publishers, send me probably 20 or 30 free books a
month. And most of these I don't have time to read. So, I have old friends that

33:50.890 --> 34:03.170
I try to keep in touch with, keep up with, but it's impossible for anybody to be
as intimately acquainted with all the field as we all were in the 30's and 40's.

34:04.110 --> 34:21.870
but we still have a fellowship, a sort of subculture that draws us together in a
way that doesn't happen to leaders of mystery or Westerns or whatever. And it

34:21.870 --> 34:35.750
seems to me that basically it's a concern with science and technology and the
impact on human beings and technology in the future We have a realization that

34:35.750 --> 34:47.910
the world is changing and a concern about what the future is going to be like.
That the layman, or the mundane, as people call them, try to forget, maybe,

34:48.210 --> 34:58.790
because if they see change at all, they're afraid of it. Yeah, I read that when
you were younger, you were sort of anti-nuclear power, and your position on that

34:58.790 --> 35:14.350
has changed over the years. Well, I'm certainly pro-nuclear power now. I'm not
sure that I was ever strongly against it except that when I heard that the atom

35:14.350 --> 35:26.990
had been split, well, I was sort of dismayed. that I had known that it was
possible, I'd written fiction about it as early as 1930, but I saw that it was

35:26.990 --> 35:38.510
going to make life complicated, and I wish that it hadn't happened in my time.
But now, since we have nuclear power, it seems to me it's the safest and most

35:38.510 --> 35:51.590
necessary development that I can see. You talk about contrasting mining coal and
nuclear power when you mine coal and bring out a lot of uranium and uranium

35:51.590 --> 36:00.310
along with it, when you burn it, when you pollute the atmosphere with a lot more
radiation and has ever escaped from a nuclear plant. You killed people in the

36:00.310 --> 36:12.430
mines and on the railways and so on and so forth, so that not nobody, to the
best of my knowledge, has just been killed in a commercial nuclear accident when

36:12.430 --> 36:24.990
we were developing steam boats under Mississippi when they blew up people every
few days and nobody thought much about it. So it seems to me that we have a sort

36:24.990 --> 36:33.250
of exaggerated fear of nuclear hazards and unwillingness

36:33.250 --> 36:53.170
to open our eyes and balance the realities and we can produce produce and use
nuclear energy nowadays and whatever else we do is going to be more expensive or

36:53.170 --> 37:03.690
more dangerous or delayed or whatever. That is, space power plants, solar power
or whatever offer glittering possibilities for the next century, but they can't

37:03.690 --> 37:14.070
do much for us in the next 10 or 20 or 30 years. Change the subject for just a
minute. How did you start to collaborate with Frederik Pohl? Well, at that

37:14.070 --> 37:28.110
time, Fred was my agent, and I sent him material, and he suggested things that
could be done with it. The first instance was something that I called the

37:28.110 --> 37:39.190
conquest of the abyss. I started out to write a novel about an undersea world,
and I pinned the bedsheet on the wall. I made maps, I did research, I described

37:39.190 --> 37:49.930
the technologies and invented people and culture and the setup. But when I got
about halfway through what was meant to be the novel, it just died. I used up

37:49.930 --> 38:03.410
all my creativity in planning it. When Fred came in, well, we got three undersea
novels about it and the reefs of space came About more the same way though I

38:03.410 --> 38:15.250
said somewhat later I'd written a 400 page draft. There was something called The
Iron Collar Man. It had the reefs of space and all the essential background in

38:15.250 --> 38:29.210
it, but I wasn't happy with it. I never did. I showed it to Fred while we
replotted it and he rewrote it. It was a very successful revision. Speaking of

38:29.210 --> 38:43.650
anticipating science, it took a long time to get that into print, and I was
afraid that people wouldn't start doing organ transplants too soon, but we did.

38:44.030 --> 38:53.690
We did the heart transplanters at least by a few years. Yeah, I read that you're
speaking of the body bank in that one. That was a lot of fun to do, and I had

38:53.690 --> 39:05.230
the body bank in my version, but Fred came up with a lot of delightfully
horrifying variations and possibilities of the body bank. Had you ever run

39:05.230 --> 39:13.410
across that in fiction before, to your knowledge? Was that the first time people
did that? Well, as far as I knew, it was new. The body bank was certainly a new

39:13.410 --> 39:25.210
phrase to me. What you...I'm still curious how... I've never understood how
someone can, say, collaborate on a novel. How does that work in your

39:25.210 --> 39:36.290
relationship? First of all, a collaboration is a pretty intimate relationship.
So like a marriage, it doesn't work unless you have a mutual trust and

39:36.290 --> 39:47.110
preferably both parties should have complimentary abilities so each one can add
something. I've collaborated with several people and always because I felt that

39:47.110 --> 39:58.510
they could do something I couldn't. The first collaboration was with Dr. Miles
J. Brewer, something like 50 years ago we wrote a novel together as well as a

39:58.510 --> 40:10.170
short story and a novel that I just re-read, and in some ways I thought it was
pretty good and I kind of apprenticed myself to Brewer, who was selling to

40:10.170 --> 40:23.410
Amazing a couple of years ahead of me, and when you look at him now he wasn't a
really brilliant writer, but he was competent and serious and took his

40:23.410 --> 40:34.950
techniques seriously, and he knew things that I wanted to learn. I did the
writing and most of the writing, and he helped with the plotting and suggested

40:34.950 --> 40:51.770
revisions and whatever. and with Fred well I respect him, first of all I like
him and then I respect his style, his editorial sense and his craftsmanship

40:51.770 --> 40:52.490
generally.

40:54.930 --> 41:07.510
When I'm working with someone like Fred, I think a writer needs an audience.
That is, communication is a two-way process. You need to know your audience, and

41:07.510 --> 41:20.550
you need to feedback from your audience. And I'm doing a first try for someone
like Fred, since I know him, it gives a kind of automatic focus. It helps

41:20.550 --> 41:33.950
crystallize the point of view. It makes the writing go a lot faster Especially
since I know that he's going to do the final draft. I don't have to worry about

41:33.950 --> 41:50.310
literary polish, the alliterations or avoiding rhyme and words. Whatever I write
down what comes. I trust him to redo it. In other words, in your relationship

41:50.310 --> 41:59.190
with him, you sort of get the ideas in the first draft and he does the revision
and polishing. That's basically it. In that book, that was a trilogy. You

41:59.190 --> 42:03.510
mentioned the reefs of space. That was a trilogy, if I recall, and the third
book was Rogue Star. Right.

42:07.010 --> 42:15.130
One of the ideas that fascinated me in that book, I think it was also in the
second book, Star Child, the concept of a sentient star and combining the

42:15.130 --> 42:28.630
intelligence with the human intelligence. That was an idea that appealed to me
tremendously, and I'm not sure where I got it. Sturgeon wrote a story long ago

42:28.630 --> 42:42.490
called Killdozer! about a sentient thing that seized a bulldozer. And my
original motion for this story was to begin with the creation of a mind that

42:42.490 --> 42:59.330
could, let's say, possess matter, could store intelligence and shifting
electronic spins or whatever. I had a technique. I wanted to tell the story

42:59.330 --> 43:13.030
completely from the viewpoint of the creature that was made in the laboratory
and enlarged itself successively until it became the mind of a star. I did the

43:13.030 --> 43:26.810
first draft of the story that way, but Fred didn't like it, felt it wasn't
successful, and so he had me do some more of material from the viewpoints of the

43:26.810 --> 43:40.530
human characters, and the stories it published has shifting points of view, and
that's one collaboration that I've always a little bit regretted because I felt

43:40.530 --> 43:53.390
that the way I wanted to do it, from the viewpoint of the alien, could have been
done and would have been something more original and difficult, although maybe

43:53.390 --> 44:06.470
harder to do. But it worked out very well as a collaboration, and evidently
there was something less than successful about my first draft, or Fred wouldn't

44:06.470 --> 44:12.590
have wanted to change it. Do you have any questions right now, David? No, I'm
fascinated so far.

